<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911203-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>911203-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Ivaco Inc.:   Firm's Plastic-Pipe Business   To Combine With Scepter's</HL><DATE>12/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   IVA.A</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>JOINT VENTURES (JVN)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CANADA (CN)NORTH AMERICA (NME)</RE><LP>   Ivaco Inc. said its Canron Inc. unit and closely heldScepter Manufacturing Co. agreed in principle to combinetheir plastic-pipe businesses.   Ivaco said the combined plastic-pipe business will be 50%owned by Canron and 50% owned by Scepter. It said thecombined business will have annual sales of about 250 millionCanadian dollars (US$220 million), about 1,000 employees and18 plants. Paul Ivanier, president and chief executive ofIvaco, said that he couldn't say if some plants will be shutas a result of the merger of the Canron and Scepterbusinesses, adding &quot;the idea isn't to close plants.&quot; Mr.Ivanier said the Canron and Scepter plastic-pipe businessesare both currently profitable.</LP><TEXT>   Terms weren't disclosed. However, Mr. Ivanier said theCanron and Scepter plastic-pipe assets to be put into thecombined business are valued equally. Ivaco said thetransaction is subject to the completion of definitiveagreements and other conditions. Ivaco is a Montreal-basedsteel-products concern. Ivaco's Canron unit and Scepter arebased in Toronto.</TEXT></DOC>